{"id":"10614","name":"Text Size","tagline":"Easily change your system's text size","icon":"ios14 c255 g59743","latest":"30891","description":"\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>Shortcuts allows changing the system's text size to specific sizes, but there's is no easy way to tell Siri to make the text larger or smaller than the current size.</p>\n<p>This shortcut is the first ingredient to solve that. It is a function that changes the text size when it receives a number between -3 and 8 (from -3 to 3 are the regular sizes, and from 4 to 8 are the accessibility ones).</p>\n<p>When it runs without input it works as a demo, letting the user to select the desired text size, and also showing the numerical value associated to each one.</p>\n<p>The second ingredient is a pair or shortcuts that change the relative text size:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://routinehub.co/shortcut/10615/\">Larger Text</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://routinehub.co/shortcut/10616/\">Smaller Text</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Those two remember the current size (changed by the \"Text Size\" shortcut) in a file in iCloud Drive. There is also available an equivalent pair of shortcuts that do the remembering using Data Jar:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://routinehub.co/shortcut/10617/\">Larger Text [DJ]</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://routinehub.co/shortcut/10618/\">Smaller Text [DJ]</a></li>\n</ul>\n\t\t\t\t","releasenotes":"<p><strong>1.0.0 - Dec. 4, 2021, 8:32 p.m.</strong></p>"}